    "content_hash": "sha256:fab9e73a1c198f844fed96d5e9c06ae956aa27b7c09b5def33869a32ea25d8a6",
    "summary": "The Battle of Tours (also called the Battle of Poitiers, October 732 AD) was the decisive engagement in which Frankish and Burgundian forces under Charles Martel (Grandfather of [[event:2138|Charlemagne]]) defeated an Umayyad army commanded by Abdul Rahman Al Ghafiqi that had crossed the Pyrenees from [[event:2131|Muslim Spain]] and was raiding deep into France. Abdul Rahman was killed in the battle; the Umayyad forces withdrew south of the Pyrenees and never again mounted a serious attempt to expand into Frankish territory. The battle is conventionally cited as the event that prevented the Islamization of western Europe.\n\nThe significance of Tours has been both celebrated and debated by historians. Western tradition — from Edward Gibbon onward — has portrayed it as a decisive civilizational watershed; modern historians tend to see it as one of several factors that limited Islamic expansion into Europe (the more important constraints being the geographic barrier of the Pyrenees, the over-extension of Umayyad supply lines, and the subsequent internal conflicts of the [[event:3521|Abbasid Revolution]]). Charles Martel's victory enhanced his political prestige enormously, providing the military credibility that would allow his son Pepin III to depose the last Merovingian king and establish the Carolingian dynasty. The battle earned Charles the epithet 'Martel' (the Hammer). Whether or not it was the decisive turning point some have claimed, it fixed the Pyrenees as the boundary between Christian and Muslim Iberia for the following 760 years.",
